    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<head>Jim to Mademoiselle Marcelle Guerin <date value="1916-01-02">Jan 2nd 1916 [1917]</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline><date value="1917-01-02">Jan 2nd 1916 [1917]</date></dateline>
        			
            <salute>
            My dear:
            </salute></opener>
        		
        		<p>
            Thank you so much
            for the hair pins, and for
            having bought the Illustration.
            I don’t know what I’d do 
            without you in this blooming
            war.  
            </p><p>
            I was very shocked and
            saddened by the news of
            Howard’s death.  I wrote to
            Mary.
            </p><p>
            Sure, take the pen down
            
            <pb n="[p.2]"/>
            
            to Virby Beards.  They ought
            to exchange it, or put in 
            a stub pen for you.  I 
            tried to get a stub for you, but the one I sent 
            was the bluntest I could get.
            </p><p>
            Bill and Johnson arrived
            last night.  Its good to
            see them back.  Hill &amp;
            Rockwell left for the States
            just as they came.
            </p><p>
            They seem to have given
            up sending us out in bad
            
            <pb n="[p.3]"/>
            
            weather.  It has been covered
            for a few days and we have
            done no flying at all.
            </p><p>
            Bill tells me the Escadrille
            has a rotten reputation in
            Paris for drinking.  I don’t
            know why for there’s been
            none of it except on
            Thanksgiving and Christmas<unclear>[.]</unclear>
            </p><p>
            I don’t really care about
            initials on the cigarette
            case, so why go to the
            
            <pb n="[p.4]"/>
            
            trouble and expense?  Its a
            beaut [sic] of a case and I don’t 
            see how I got along without
            it before.
            </p><p>
            "Whiskey" gets more gentil [sic]
            every day.  He’s a big chap
            now.
            </p><p>
            Haven’t heard from Mrs.
            Weeks yet.
            </p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <salute>Good night, Marcelle,</salute>
            
            <signed>Jim</signed>
        		</closer>
        		
            
            <!-- [With this letter is an envelope addressed to Mademoiselle Marcelle Guerin, 148 Bis Rue de Longchamp, XVI, Paris.] -->  
            
            </div1>
